B.W.\n|\\VA/INj Company District 0*33\nWanted Loads From\nCalifornia. Maine. Vermont. Florida and\npoints South.\nTo or From\nBuffalo. St. Paul. Chicago. Cincinnati.\nKansas City Milwaukee or any Eastern city.\nRED BALL TRANSIT CO.\nNational J*l\u00ab.\nWaNTTED\u2014RETURN LOADS. NEW YORK\nCity. Vermont. New Hampshire. Asheville\nIN. C). points South. Long-distance mov\n-4 Ins our specialty. _\nSmith s Transfer Storage\nCompany.\nl 1313 YOU St North \u00bb343\nFurniture Repairing,\nUpholstering,\nChair Caneing\nCLAY ARMSTRONG\n1235 JOth St N.We\nMetropolitan 2062\nFAMOUS PASSION PLAY ACTOR AND HIS FAMILY\nH||k IL 'ijfjyNmjllr Jf Iff\nAdolph Fassnacht. famous Christus with the Frleburg Passion Players, photographed with his wife and daughter.\nFassnacht has been s Passion Player all his life, starting at the age of 4 months as the Babe in the manger.\n\u2014Star Staff Photo.\nUPTURN IN TRADE j\nNOTED IN SURVEY\nFavorable Factor Set Forth\nby National Body, but No\nConclusions Drawn.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNumerous factors favorable to future\nbusiness, both in this country and\nabroad, were seen today in a summary\nof economic conditions issued by the\nNational Business Survey Conference.\nJulius H. Barnes, chairman of the\norganization which was set up by busi\nness and finance a year ago at the sug\ngestion of President Hoover, pointed to\nthese factors in an accompanying re\nport, but left the drawing of conclu\nsions to each individual.\n\u201cIn the preparation of this sum\nmary several factors were apparent,\u201d\nthe report said. \u201cAmong these were\nthe large amount of new capital pro\nvided for productive purposes and evi\ndences of stablizatlon or advancing ten\ndencies in prices of raw materials. All\nsuch factors each business man will\nwish to weigh for herself.\u201d\nLending on Increase.\nSupporting this conclusion, it was\npointed out that lending operations of\nbanks bad markedly increased; that\ncapital issues for September were 80\nper cent greater than those of August\nand that \u2019\u2019a decreasing number of fore\nclosures and delinquencies reflected con\ntinued improvement in the field of first\nlien banking.\u201d No uniform trend,\neither up or down, was visible as to\nsavings deposits.\nInstallment selling of automobiles\nand other items was said to be show\ning \u201cno material increase in reposses\nsions.\u201d Some betterment exists in\nwholesale gollectlons, with no change\nin retail collections. Life insurance\nselling increased in September over Au\ngust. Premium Income of fire Insur\nance companies has declined.\nFor the first nine months of 1930.\nthe report said, residential construc\ntion had declined under last year's\nmark by $714,000,000, but public works\nand public utility construction had been\nabove last year\u2019s volume by $180,000,-\n000. Paving contracts exceeded last\nyear\u2019s total by 7 per cent. Residential\nvacancies over the country were normal\nfor September in 6 out of 17 districts\nof the United States.\nStreet Car Traffic Off.\nStreet railway traffic in September\nwas 8 per cent under that of the same\nmonth last year, but August records of\nsuch traffic were 10 per cent under last\nyear\u2019s. Freight traffic on railroads was\nless.\nSeasonal Increases were noted In\ntelephone communications and in radio\nsales. Postal receipts showed a decline\nIn the previous rate of recession for\nSeptember.\nNew capital Investments In utilities\ncontinued to be above last year\u2019s rec\nords in most cases. Output of electrical\nequipment was above 1928 levels, though\nbelow that of 1929. Stocks on hand of\npetroleum products declined. Metal\nprices dropped, and output rates in steel\nand copper were lower than the aver\nage. September automobile production\nwas 42 per cent below that of last year,\nbut Inventories of auto tires have de\ncreased.\nSeasonal Gains Noted.\nProduction of cottonseed products and\nindustrial alcohol has been at high\nrates, the report said. September also\n\u201ccarried forward the seasonal improve\nment in the textile industry,\u201d with in\ncreased takings of cotton by mills.\nConsumption of silk markedly Increased,\nj Export demand for apples was greater\ni than last year, while domestic shlp\ni ments of fruits and vegetables remained\nat 1929 levels.\ni Milk consumption has held firm, but\nin \u201cterms of consumer outlay\u201d produce\nwas said to have brought in 15 per cent\nless during September than over a five\nyear average. Stocks of raw sugar have\ndeclined and prices risen.\n\u201cA number of raw materials now show\nincreases in price,\u2019\u2019 the report noted,\nnaming cotton, com, wheat and coffee.\nForeign trade volume was said to have\ndeclined, but it added that abroad there\n\u201cwere promising signs of stable condi\ntions and also of improvement in va\nriety of industries, scattered through\nmany countries.\u201d\nr 9\nDISCUSSION DEMANDED\nReichstag Group to Discuss Re\nvision of Versailles Treaty.\nBERLIN. October 27 UP).\u2014Revision\nof the Versailles peace treaty and a\nmoratorium on the Young plan will be\ndiscussed by the Foreign Affairs Com\nmittee of the Reichstag on Wednesday\nat the demand of Fascist members.\nDiscussion of these highly touchy\nsubjects does not, however, necessarily\ninvolve action on them. The six Fas\ncist members of the committee have\nthe right to insist on the discussion,\nbut must reckon with the 22 other\nmembers in any voting.\nWill Rogers\nSays:\nSANTA MONICA, Calif.\u2014Oo-La-\nOah. Okla.. my real old home, bad a\nfine celebration Saturday. Sure sorry\ncouldn\u2019t make it Unemployment is\nterrible. But employment is worse.\nA prominent miniature golf course\nout here was robbed the other night.\nThe bandits got 5 \u201cputters.\u201d 13 balls\nand 85 cents in currency.\nStanford University has always been\nkinder hard to get into, but after yes*\nterd&y\u2019s game with Southern California\nthey would take In any moron that\ncouldn\u2019t even spell foot ball, aa long as\nhe looked like he could carry one,\n\nTHE EVENING STAB, WASHINGTON. D. C.. MONDAY. OCTOBER 27. 7930.\nI TWO MEN HANGED\nCLAIMED SUICIDES\nUnidentified Bodies Found on\nSuccessive Days Dangling From\nTrees in Detroit.\n\nBy the Associated Press.\nDETROIT, October 27.\u2014The bod\nies of two unidentified men have\nbeen found hanging in trees here dur\ning the past two days.\nSaturday a body was found in a tree\nnear the intersection of Allen road and\nPennsylvania avenue. A second body\nwas found yesterday in a park near\nthe Michigan State Fair Grounds. Both\nwere pronounced \u201cobvious cases of sui\ncide\u201d by the Wyane County coroner.\nThe body found Saturday was that of i\na man about 40 years of age. The belt\nbuckle was engraved with the initials\n\u201cA. K.\u201d and the clothing bore trade I\nmarks of New York clothiers. The j\nman who hanged himself yesterday was j\nabout 60. A pawn ticket found in the\nclothing was made out to Gus Berg.\nMISSION OBSERVES\n46TH ANNIVERSARY\nLeaden of Central Union Hold Re\nvival Meetings\u2014ls Churches\nAid Celebration.\nHie Central Union Mission brought\nthe celebration of its forty-sixth\nanniversary to a close yesterday with\ntwo large revival meetings, one held in\nthe afternoon at the Calvary Baptl t\nChurch and the other in the evening at\nthe Gunton Temple Memorial Presby\nterian Church. Visiting mission workers\nfrom cities also spoke from pulpits of\n15 Protestant churches in the Interests\nof the mission over which Supt. and\nMrs. John S. Bennett have presided for\n15 years.\nHomer Rodeheaver, whose singing\nand trombone playing have been a\nfeature of the celebration, performed\nat the two mass meetings and In the\nmorning he spoke at the First Congre\ngational Church. Mr. Rodeheaver was\nassisted by his sister, Mrs. Ruth\nThomas, in the singing of some of the\nspirituals and popular revival songs.\nWork of Men\u2019s Department Shown.\nAt last night\u2019s meeting, Mr. Bennett\nspoke about the work of the men's\nlepaitment at the mission and the needs\nof the approaching Winter. Other\nspeakers included Rev. Henry H. Hadley\nof the Calvary Episcopal Mission of New\nYork, who had preached earlier in the\nday at the Mount Vernon Place M. E.\nChurch.\nAt both meetings, the testimony of\nformer \u201cdown and out\u201d men proved a\ni feature and many others professed\nconversions. E. H. DeOroot, president\ni of the mission\u2019s board of directors,\ni presided at each session.\nDr. Join Morley, superintendent of the\nWest Side Mission of New York; Harry\nHaines, noted convert of the Eighth\nAvenue Mission of that city, and Henry\nReinhart of the City Mission, Harris\n-1 burg, Pa., spoke at Calvary Church\ni meeting in the afternoon. Mrs. Ben\nnett also told of the work of the\nl Children\u2019s Emergency Home which is\nI always filled to capacity, she said, and\nhas succeeded in sending many worthy\ni girls through school. Thomas Moss,\norganist at the Calvary Church,\nfurnished the incidental music.\nChnrches Co-operate.\nIn the morning at Calvary Church.\n1 John R. Mclntyre, mission worker of\n1 Germantown, Pa. preached from the\npulpit. Others who preached at local\nchurches in behalf of the mission ln\neluded; Lawrence Sutherland of\nNewark. N. J., Eastern Presbyterian\nChurch; Harry Haines of Newark,\nEpworth M. E. Church; Rev. A. L.\nJones, superintendent of the McAuley\nI Mission, New York City, Fifteenth\nStreet Christian Church; Dr. John Mor\n-1 ley of New York, Georgetown Lutheran\nChurch; WUliam H. Ramsey, trustee of\nthe Central Union Mission, Marvin M.\nE. Church South; R\u00abv. H. H. Kratzig,\nNorfolk, Va., Metropolitan M. E. Church;\nDr. W. E. Paul, Minneapolis, Minn.,\nj National Baptist Memorial Church; J.\nArthur Schlichter, Philadelphia, Rhode\nIsland Avenue M. P. Church; Edgar\nJones, Worcester. Mass., North Carolina\nM. P. Church; Henry Reinhart, Harrls\nj burg, Pa., Sherwood Presbyterian\nChurch, R. D. Murphy, Temple Baptist,\n1 and Dr. Morley, at the Central Presby\nterian Church in the evening.\n$3,000,000,000 INVOLVED\nIN CASES LITIGATED\nCourt of Clalma at Present Session\nConsidering 2,000 Separate Tax\nand Contract Controversies.\nBy the Associated Press.\nTwo thousand cases involving almost\n$3,000,000,000 are before the Court of\nClaims at its present session.\nArising principally out of government\ncontracts and tax cases, the suits in\nvolve almost every possible claim that\ncan be made against the government.\nThey Include actions for requisition of\nships and railroads; transportation of\ntroops, ammunition and supplies, con\ntracts for anti-aircraft engines and guns\nand myriad tax actions.\nDespite the number of cases filed, the\ncourt is up with its trial calendar and\nthat in the face of a heavy increase\nin the number of cases during the last\nten years. There were only 733 on its\ndocket on July 1, 1921.\nIn come suits the Government not\nonly successfully defends itself against\nthe plaintiffs claim but recovers a\ncounter-claim. Such Judgments in\nfavor of the government during the\nlast fiscal year brought, in $1,460,574.55.\nJudgments against the government,\nhowever, amounted to $14,238,632.\nA novel pair of nut-crackers which\nhas met with the approval of the Prince\nof Wales consists of two golf clubs\nplaced with heads together.\nFASSNACHT TELLS\nPASSION PLAY NEED\nPortrayer of Christ Thinks\nAmerica Will Profit By\nand Appreciates Role.\nForty-nine years ago a 4-month-old\nbaby boy appeared In the role of Jesus\nChrist with the Freiburg Passion Play\nj ers in Freiburg, Germany. The child\nI was Adolph Fassnacht, who makes his\n1 first appearanceffn Washington tonight.\nFassnacht was literally bom in his\npart, his father and grandfather be\nfore him having devoted their lives to\nthe same role.\nThe purpose of the play, as he sees\nit, is simply to carry the message of\nChrist\u2019s life to the world.\nFirst Visit in 1928.\nHe first came to the United States\nwith his company in 1928, opening at\nSt. Joseph, Mo. In the two years that\nfollowed he traveled over the country,\ngoing from city to city in an automobile\nin order to acquire first-hand impres\nsions of the American people.\n\u201cI believe,\u201d he said, \u201cthat there is\nneed in America for the Passion Play,\nand that our efforts are appreciated by\nyour people.\n\u201cMany, no doubt, come to our per\nformances from mere curiosity, but I\nam sure they leave with the message\nof Jesus Christ deeply implanted in\ntheir minds.\u201d\nMr. Fassnacht is singularly direct\nand simple in his manner.\nRole Is Life Work.\n\u201cMy entire life is wrapped up in the\nPassion Play,\u201d he said. \u201cIt has been\nthe life work of my family for genera\ntions, and to me it is more than the\nmere playing of a part.\n\u201cI am happy if I can help my audi\nences visualize the life of Christ as I\nsee it. That has been the purpose of\nthe Passion Players since *the first pro\nduction in 1264, and it is a mission,\nwhich, for me, can never be altered.\u201d\nMr. Fassnacht supervises the details\nof preparing for each performance per\nsonally, and these additional duties oc\ncupy a great deal of his time.\nBelieves Youth Sound.\n\u201cIt is fatiguing,\u201d he said, \u201cand in the\nday I am very tired. But at night,\nwhen the play begins, it is different.\nThen all weariness is forgotten and the\nplay is the thing.\u201d\nHe does not believe that the youth of\nAmerica is decadent or that it need\nworry especially over its salvation.\n\u201cBut,\u201d he repeated, \u201cit is good for\nthem to see the play for cultural rea\nsons.\u201d\nIllinois Mine to Be Beopened.\nHARRISBURG, 111., October 27 OP).\u2014\nMine No. 12 here of the Ogara Co.,\nwhich has been idle since July 31, will\nreopen today, giving full time employ\nment to 450 men.\nTwo women are training as air pilots\nto every three men in England.\n_____\nYOUR CAR\nWASHED CLEAN\n15 15\nMinutes v Minutes\nNo Additional Charge on\nSat., Sun. or Holidays\nSIMONIZING EXPERTS\nPolishing, Greasing, Motor\nCleaning\nNU-WAY AUTO LAUNDRY\n24-26 H St. N.E.\n1\nMILK PROVEN\nExtra Safe, Extra Rich\nBY EVERY KNOWN LABORATORY TEST!\nNo method is too meticulous\u2014no test too exacting\nfor Chestnut Farms Milk! We leave nothing to chance! WT\"\nSuperior Quality\u2014day in\nextra\"p\"rote<Son! e piace\n*&6e4tmU\nSelected, as the. WO/UOSMODCL Qt/KS.FLA/fT (7 jUT\nL\nHARRISON SCORES\nCHARGE BY FESS\nDemocrats Aid Rather Than\nGloat Over Depression,\nSays Senator.\nThe recent charge by Chairman Fess\nof the Republican National Committee\nthat the Democrats \u201care unable to con\nceal their actual pleasure over the\ncountry\u2019s depression\u201d was declared last\nnight by Senator Harrison, Democrat, of\nMississippi, to be \u201cunjustified by the\nfacts.\u201d\n\u201cThroughout this crisis,\u201d Harrison\nsaid in a statement through the Demo\nj cratic National Committee, \"the Demo\ncratic minorities in Congress have co\noperated in the fullest measure, first, in\ntrying to prevent it, and thenjn trying\nto restore confidence.\n\"If it was harmful for Democratic\nleadership in the beginning to warn the\nPresident, Senator Fess and his col\nleagues of the inevitable consequences\nof the passage of the tariff law, then\nwe are guilty.\n\u201cThe pitiable picture is that the\nPresident and Senator Fess and other\nRepublican leaders in the Congress, re\nfused to accept our advice or be in\nfluenced by our action. But in every\nattempt to revive business confidence,\nrestore economic stability, whether in\nstituted by the President of not, we\nunreservedly and pnstlntedly co-oper\nated.\u201d\nROAD ENGINEER DIES\nMaj. Blauvelt Built $40,000,000\nMaryland Toxic Gas Plant.\nDENVER, Colo., October 27 OP).\nLouis D. Blauvelt, 63, Colorado State\nhighway engineer, who as a war-time\nArmy major planned and built a $40,-\n000,000 toxic gas plant at Edgewater\nArsenal in Maryland, died here yester\nday.\nFill Your\u2018Bins With HEALTH\nHealth for next Winter\u2014dependable, steady\ncomfort\u2014that\u2019s what you get when you buy\nReading Anthracite from Marlow. And clean?\n\u2014you\u2019ve never seen a cleaner fuel than this\nbrilliant black hard coal! Call us now\u2014don\u2019t\nput it off another day!\nMarlow Coal Co.\n811 E St. N.W. NAtional 0311\nBig Business\nMakes Lower Prices\nWe are selling more Palms, Ferns and other House\nPlants during our ANNUAL FALL SALE than in any\nprevious season.\nVolume business justifies smaller prices with us.\nSmall Cacti, 50c Pandann., $2.00\nTable Ferns, SI.OO Kentia Palms, $3.00 and np.\n6-inch Boston Forns, $1.25 Old-Fashioned Rubber Plants,\nBird\u2019s-Nast Farns, $1.50 SI.OO\nDracenas, SI.OO Pteris Farns, in saveral varie-\nSuHTim.it SI.OO ti.. 25c and 50c.\nlights\"\njt CHOBTT SAYS \u2014\u201cOId and Cold are twin trouble\ns VLn/ A, mskert. No metoriat with foreiisht will be\nmarooned thi* Winter by s dead battery. We esn\nC' JT rechsrse er repair what you have, maybe\u2014but my\nf i 1 Mus auareatlon ie new FIRESTONE Battery\u2014SFEClAL\nA I LY BUILT TO WITHSTAND THE RAVAGES OF\nI WINTER. It\u2019ll warm your heart by Ita performance.\u2019*\nW 13 277 3 UST\nfjKrJA fiftltOttC TIRES AND BATTERIES\nMORROW IGNORES\nFIERY OPPONENT\nJersey Senatorial Candidates\nDiffer Widely\u2014Hot Con\ntests for House..\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEWARK, N. J., October 27.\u2014The\ncontest lor United States Senator in\nNew Jersey has robbed this year's cam\npaign of the usual apathy bf an off-year.\nDwight W. Morrow became a candi\ndate just a few months ago and the\nNation took notice. He was a fresh\nfigure in the game of politics, which\nnow has him pitted against Alexander\nSimpson and Miss Thelma Parkinson,\nDemocrats, and against the nominees\nof the Prohibition, Communist and\nSocialist parties.\nSimpson is a candidate for the full\nsenatorial term of six years. Miss\nParkinson went from Smith College into\npolitics.\nFor the most part, New Jersey has\nturned its eyes and ears toward two\nmen, heard both of them renounce pro\nhibition, one of th?m laud President\nHoover, the other bitterly assail him.\nAnswers No Questions.\nMorrow answers no charges. He does\nnot mention his adversaries. Neither\ndoes he criticize the issues they raise.\nHe makes no specific requests for votes\nfor himself: he asks only that the peo\nple exercise their franchise.\nSimpson, spectacular of speech, has\nraised a warning against support of\nindorsers of President Hoover and the\nnational administration, lest business\ndepression continue.\nSimpson is a man of slogans and al\nliterations. Morrow is \"Dwight Worship\nMorrow\u2019\u2019 to Simpson. A vote for the\nRepublican, he warns, is signification of\napproval of \"Morrow, Morgan and\nmisery.\u201d\nMorrow was formerly a partner of\nJ. P. Morgan St Co.\nMorrow, warmly commending Presi\ndent Hoover, holds that the courage\nof the people will constitute the major\ncontribution to the return of prosperity.\nHe pleads against exaggeration of busi\nness depression and unemployment.\nSince his declaration for repeal of the\neighteenth amendment. Morrow has\nbeen advanced as a potential candidate\nfor the presidency. He refuses to take\nsuch talk seriously. He has said he\nlooks forward with \"confidence and\nwith pleasure\u201d to voting for the re\nnomination and re-election of President\nHoover In 1932.\nA full delegation of 12 will be elected\nto the House of Representatives, a\ncomplement of 60 sent to the State As\nsembly and State Senators chosen.\nOs the 12 Representatives In the\nHouse, only two are Democrats. Four\nof the districts now represented by Re\npublicans are conceded to be in doubt,\nthe third, sixth, eighth and ninth.\nThree former Representatives are seek\ning to return.\nIn the third district. In a field of\nfive candidates, Thomas M. Gopsill, Re\npublican. and William H. Sutphin,\nDemocrat, are waging a struggle for\nthe seat relinquished by Representative\nHarold O. Hoffman, who became State\ncommissioner of motor vehicles. Oop\nsill indorsed Morrow's prohibition stand\nand Sutphin Is against prohibition.\nDry Stand Maintained.\nRepresentative Randolph Perkins of\nthe sixth district has maintained his at\ntitude in favor of prohibition, while\nArchibald C. Hart, Democratic candi\ndate and three-time member of Con\ngress, is against prohibition.\nRepresentative Franklin W. Fort, un\nsuccessful candidate in the Republican\nprimary for nomination to the United\nStates Senate as upholder of the eight\neenth amendment, will relinquish his\noffice next March and two opponents\nof prohibition are making a strong fight\nto succeed him. Peter A. Cavicchia won\nthe Republican nomination and Daniel\nF. Mtnahan, former Democratic Repre\nsentative, is opposing him, in the ninth\ndistrict.\nFred A. Hartley, Jr., who won elec\ntion as Representative from the eighth\ndistrict by a slight majority over Paul\nJ. Moore in a presidential year, is seek\ning re-election.\na.\nif Don\u2019t target Or our phone\nthe address number U w\nI <g|\u00bbe SHADER I\nJ ,f 4 a When your\n830 13th St. N.W.I A 1 District 3324-33251 du Pont\n(Am W 8TO 8 \u00bbAMMON* shades \u00b0bZ\nE&;:\ntbs WASBABZS window ssah\u00bb fi7.^! b\nM Te Identify the original washable, isnproof Tontine\nShade Cloth ask to be ahowa this trade mark. SSsS_^==<\nC Our factory-made-to-\nmeasure shades are\nC found in the\nS Best Homes J\n\nc Kenwood\nThe Community With Assured Future\nWhile the conception of Kenwood is ideal\nistic, it is being developed with the utmost\npracticality\u2014with regulations that do not\ncurtail the exercise of the fullest freedom by\nindividual investors, }>ut stringent enough to\npreserve the fundamental ideals for all time.\nFurnished Exhibit Home\n301 Brookaide Drive\nWe hope you\u2019ll take occasion to inspect it in Its\nappropriate dress by W. B. Moses Sons. Open\nfrom 10 a.m. to 9 p.m.\nGo west of Wisconsin Avenue on Bradley\ncontinuing under the viaduct to the\nentrance to Kenwood, three short squares\nto the left.\nKennedy-Chamherlm Development Co.\n2400 Sixteenth Street Columbia 7280\n\nHUH RICH CREAM\n\u2014N -pUJTTL^\n||?Sj( s REAM-TOP\nFj .f|| At No Extra Cost!\nm lfl\\\\ Wise\u2019, \u201cCREAM TOP\u201d milk\n\u2019\"JtJ !i\\ doesn\u2019t cost you one cent more\nm| II than ordinary milk.\n0 if/ V Yet it gives cream that is\nzC/i richer than the cream generally\nHj\\ e? obtained from milk \u2014cream rich\nw\\ enough to whip for coffee,\ncereals, fruit end desserts.\n\u2019Phone West 0183\ntffittUrolhert\nChew Chase Dairy\nMain Odbe A Plant 3204-M N Street N.W.\nA-3\nILLINOIS MINERS FIGHT\nUSE OF MACHINES\nCommittee to Present -fnemploy\nment Plea to Governor.\nAnother Coming Here.\nBy the Associated Press.\nMARION, 111.. October 27.\u2014A cam\npaign against all mechanical devices in\nIllinois mines, which greatly reduce the\nnumber of miners employed, has been\nlaunched by a committee of miners\nrepresenting both the Lewis and Howat\nfactions of the United Mine Workers of\nAmerica.\nApproximately 100 Southern Illinois\nminers gathered here yesterday to con\nsider possible action on a resolution\ncalling upon miners to \"cease work of\nmechanical devices injhe mines on and\nafter November 15, 1930.\" John Gerard\nof Johnston City, a member of the\nLewis faction, indorsed the campaign,\nbut urged miners to take the matter up\nwith coal company officials, instead of\n1 calling a strike.\nThe miners have appointed a com\nmittee to confer with Gov. Emmerson\u2019a\nCommission on Unemployment. The\ncommittee will report that many miners\nare out of work and some of their\nfamilies starving, because mechanical\ndevices, especially loading machines,\nmake, it impossible for many men to\nfind work. The same committee will\ngo to Washington to confer with Presi\ndent Hoover\u2019s Commission on Unem\nployment, and there they will report\nthat present freight rates discriminate\nagainst Illinois coal in favor of Ken\ntucky coal.\nPort Improvements, road extensions\nand repairs and the exploitation of\nwater power resources are proceeding\nrapidly in all of Syria under French\nmandate.","height":"25449","width":"19839"}}
